<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-827-516  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 827 516.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>CommunicationsWeek  Oct 30 1989 n272 p70(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The first broadband telecom switch? (Berlin, Germany beta testsasynchronous transfer mode broadband telecommunications switchfrom Siemens AG)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Gilhooly, Denis.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>West Germany is testing the first broadband telecommunicationsswitch based on the asynchronous transfer mode (ATM) packetswitching technology.andP;  The switch, manufactured and installed inthe city of Berlin's experimental fiber optic network, is seen asthe foundation for public and private networks in the late 1990s.andO;Among the far-ranging applications being tested are high-speeddata communications with digital PBX interconnection at 2M-bps and34M-bps to the 140M-bps ATM exchange.andP;  The $3 billion developmentpromises an array of applications, from video telephones tocomputer-generated pictures.andP;  The ATM switch is held to be thecrucial mainstay of broadband network development.andP;  It enables aflexible approach that divides bit streams into packets of varyinglengths and sending them over a common digital transport path.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Siemens AG (products).andO;Topic:     West GermanyBeta TestingFiber OpticsPacket SwitchingBroadbandData CommunicationsData Transfer RateSwitches.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>